# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gin-web-go
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:gin-web-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:gin-web-go/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:gin-web-go/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:gin-web-go/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:gin-web-go/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:gin-web-go/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
